faq:
  eyebrow: "Before you arrive"
  heading: "Frequently asked questions"
  intro: "A few questions that come up often before a first session. If yours is not here, please reach out to the practice directly."
  items:
    - question: "How do I know whether I need psychotherapy or counselling?"
      answer: "Counselling tends to focus on a defined difficulty in the present — a particular relationship, a recent loss, the pressure of a specific period at work. Psychotherapy is for when something keeps repeating, or when a feeling seems out of proportion to whatever triggered it, and you want to understand why. The line between the two is rarely clean. Work that begins as short-term counselling often opens into psychotherapeutic territory; people who arrive expecting depth work sometimes need practical help first. The first consultation is where this is worked out together."
    - question: "Does Bupa, AXA or Vitality cover sessions with you?"
      answer: "The practice is recognised by Bupa, AXA Health, Vitality and Cigna. Coverage for psychotherapy varies considerably between policies, and it is worth checking the specifics of yours before a first session. Receipts can be issued in the format insurers usually ask for: modality, session length, practitioner registration."
    - question: "How many sessions will I need?"
      answer: "It depends on what you bring and what you find. For some people, eight to twelve focused sessions are enough, and we will say so when that is true. For others, the work unfolds over a longer period — sometimes years — particularly when it moves into analytical territory. The frame is discussed openly at the beginning and reviewed at intervals throughout. When a piece of work feels finished, it is named as such."
    - question: "Are sessions in London, or can you work online?"
      answer: "Both. In person at Harley Street, Mayfair, Bermondsey or Colchester; online for clients anywhere in the world. The same practitioner can hold the work across formats, so a course of therapy that begins in the consulting room can move online when life changes — or the other way around."
    - question: "What makes Philippe Jacquet & Associates different?"
      answer: "There are several capable psychotherapists in London. What distinguishes this practice is a doctoral specialism in male eating disorders that does not really exist elsewhere in Europe, a senior team that takes Jungian analytical work seriously, and a willingness to see clients outside standard hours and outside standard records when professional or family circumstances require it."
    - question: "Are online therapy sessions as effective as in-person therapy?"
      answer: "For most presentations, yes. The research on online psychotherapy in anxiety, depression and several trauma protocols now shows outcomes comparable to in-person work. The exceptions tend to involve embodied or somatic processes — deeper trauma work in particular — where the physical setting carries some of the therapeutic weight. We will say at the consultation if your case sits in that category."
    - question: "Can psychotherapy help with work-related stress, anxiety or burnout?"
      answer: "Yes, and a substantial part of the practice does exactly this. The work often runs along two tracks at once: addressing what is happening now — the sleep, the irritability, the dread of the working week — and looking at why this particular working life has become unsustainable in this particular way. For senior professionals and clients with demanding schedules, evening and out-of-hours appointments are routinely available."
    - question: "How confidential are psychotherapy and counselling sessions in London?"
      answer: "Confidentiality is the ground of any clinical work. The law requires it, professional registration requires it, and the practice would not be functional without it. For clients who need additional discretion — public figures, regulated professions, sensitive personal circumstances — further arrangements can be made: appointments outside business hours, attendance under arrangements set up directly with the practice, paper records where preferred. The narrow exceptions to confidentiality are explained at the first session."
    - question: "What qualifications should a psychotherapist or hypnotherapist in London have?"
      answer: "Psychotherapy is not a protected title in the United Kingdom, which means anyone may use it. The substantive marker of qualification is registration with a professional body: UKCP, BACP, BPC or BPS for psychotherapy; the GHR or GHSC for hypnotherapy. Every practitioner working at Philippe Jacquet & Associates is registered and accountable to the relevant body. When considering any practitioner, that registration is the thing to verify."
    - question: "How much does psychotherapy cost per session?"
      answer: "Fees vary by location, by session length, and by the type of work. Rather than publish a price list that would mislead in one direction or another, the practice prefers to quote directly. A short message describing what you have in mind — the kind of presentation, the location or online preference, whether you are looking for a single therapist or a fuller assessment — will be answered with a clear figure."
